{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# 04 - Job Clustering & Topic Modeling\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook explores job clustering using K-Means to identify natural job families. We will determine the optimal number of clusters using the Elbow Method and Silhouette Score. Additionally, we will visualize the clusters using PCA and perform optional LDA Topic Modeling to extract in-demand skill themes for richer skill gap analysis, as outlined in the project brief."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from sklearn.cluster import KMeans\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score\n",
    "from sklearn.decomposition import PCA\n",
    "from sklearn.manifold import TSNE\n",
    "from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer\n",
    "from gensim.models import LdaModel\n",
    "from gensim.corpora import Dictionary\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "import pickle\n",
    "import os\n",
    "import sys\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add src to path\n",
    "sys.path.append(os.path.join(os.path.dirname(os.path.dirname(os.path.abspath(__file__))), 'src'))\n",
    "from config import CLEANED_JOB_DATA_PATH, JOB_VECTORIZER_PATH, CLUSTERING_MODEL_PATH, FIGURE_DIR\n",
    "from data.preprocess import preprocess_job_data\n",
    "from features.text_features import load_vectorizer\n",
    "\n",
    "# Ensure directories exist\n",
    "os.makedirs(FIGURE_DIR, exist_ok=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Load Data and TF-IDF Features\n",
    "\n",
    "We load the preprocessed job dataset and the TF-IDF vectorizer for job descriptions. If not available, we run the preprocessing step."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if not os.path.exists(CLEANED_JOB_DATA_PATH):\n",
    "    print("Cleaned job data not found. Running preprocessing...")\n",
    "    job_df = preprocess_job_data()\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print("Loading cleaned job data...")\n",
    "    job_df = pd.read_csv(CLEANED_JOB_DATA_PATH)\n",
    "\n",
    "job_vectorizer = load_vectorizer(JOB_VECTORIZER_PATH)\n",
    "if job_df is not None and job_vectorizer is not None:\n",
    "    job_df['cleaned_text'] = job_df['cleaned_text'].fillna('')\n",
    "    tfidf_matrix = job_vectorizer.transform(job_df['cleaned_text'])\n",
    "    print("Job TF-IDF matrix shape:", tfidf_matrix.shape)\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    tfidf_matrix = None\n",
    "    print("Job data or vectorizer not loaded. Please run 01_eda.ipynb and 03_recommender.ipynb first.")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Determine Optimal Number of Clusters (K-Means)\n",
    "\n",
    "We use the Elbow Method and Silhouette Score to find the optimal number of clusters (`k`) for K-Means clustering."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if tfidf_matrix is not None:\n",
    "    # Elbow Method\n",
    "    sse = []\n",
    "    k_range = range(2, 15) # Test k from 2 to 14\n",
    "    for k in k_range:\n",
    "        kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)\n",
    "        kmeans.fit(tfidf_matrix)\n",
    "        sse.append(kmeans.inertia_)\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
    "    plt.plot(k_range, sse, marker='o')\n",
    "    plt.title('Elbow Method for Optimal K')\n",
    "    plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (K)')\n",
    "    plt.ylabel('SSE (Sum of Squared Errors)')\n",
    "    plt.grid(True)\n",
    "    plt.savefig(os.path.join(FIGURE_DIR, 'elbow_method.png'))\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Silhouette Score\n",
    "    silhouette_scores = []\n",
    "    for k in k_range:\n",
    "        kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)\n",
    "        cluster_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(tfidf_matrix)\n",
    "        if len(np.unique(cluster_labels)) > 1: # Silhouette score requires > 1 cluster\n",
    "            silhouette_scores.append(silhouette_score(tfidf_matrix, cluster_labels))\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            silhouette_scores.append(0) # Or handle as appropriate\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
    "    plt.plot(k_range, silhouette_scores, marker='o')\n",
    "    plt.title('Silhouette Score for Optimal K')\n",
    "    plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (K)')\n",
    "    plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score')\n",
    "    plt.grid(True)\n",
    "    plt.savefig(os.path.join(FIGURE_DIR, 'silhouette_score.png'))\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Based on the plots, choose an optimal K (e.g., 10 as a reasonable default)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. K-Means Clustering\n",
    "\n",
    "We apply K-Means clustering with the chosen optimal number of clusters (defaulting to 10 for demonstration purposes, as suggested in the PDF)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if tfidf_matrix is not None:\n",
    "    n_clusters = 10  # Optimal K determined from Elbow/Silhouette or default\n",
    "    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, random_state=42, n_init=10)\n",
    "    job_df['cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(tfidf_matrix)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Save the clustering model\n",
    "    with open(CLUSTERING_MODEL_PATH, 'wb') as f:\n",
    "        pickle.dump(kmeans, f)\n",
    "    print(f"K-Means clustering model saved to {CLUSTERING_MODEL_PATH}")\n",
    "    \n",
    "    print("\nJob distribution per cluster:")\n",
    "    print(job_df['cluster'].value_counts().sort_index())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Visualization: PCA for Cluster Visualization\n",
    "\n",
    "To visualize the clusters in 2D, we reduce the dimensionality of the TF-IDF matrix using Principal Component Analysis (PCA)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if tfidf_matrix is not None and job_df is not None:\n",
    "    pca = PCA(n_components=2, random_state=42)\n",
    "    components = pca.fit_transform(tfidf_matrix.toarray()) # Convert sparse matrix to dense for PCA\n",
    "    \n",
    "    pca_df = pd.DataFrame(data=components, columns=['PC1', 'PC2'])\n",
    "    pca_df['cluster'] = job_df['cluster']\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\n",
    "    sns.scatterplot(\n",
    "        x='PC1', y='PC2',\n",
    "        hue='cluster',\n",
    "        palette=sns.color_palette('hsv', n_clusters),\n",
    "        data=pca_df,\n",
    "        legend='full',\n",
    "        alpha=0.6\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    plt.title('Job Clusters visualized with PCA')\n",
    "    plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1')\n",
    "    plt.ylabel('Principal Component 2')\n",
    "    plt.savefig(os.path.join(FIGURE_DIR, 'job_clusters_pca.png'))\n",
    "    plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. Optional: LDA Topic Modeling for Skill Themes\n",
    "\n",
    "To extract in-demand skill themes for richer skill gap analysis, we can apply Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) topic modeling on the job descriptions. This helps in understanding the underlying topics or skill sets prevalent in each job cluster."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if job_df is not None:\n",
    "    # Tokenize and create dictionary and corpus for LDA\n",
    "    texts = [doc.split() for doc in job_df['cleaned_text'].tolist()]\n",
    "    dictionary = Dictionary(texts)\n",
    "    corpus = [dictionary.doc2bow(text) for text in texts]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Train LDA model\n",
    "    num_topics = 5 # Example number of topics\n",
    "    lda_model = LdaModel(corpus=corpus, id2word=dictionary, num_topics=num_topics, random_state=42, passes=10)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    print("\nLDA Topics and Keywords:")\n",
    "    for idx, topic in lda_model.print_topics(-1):\n",
    "        print(f"Topic: {idx} \nWords: {topic}\n")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Assign dominant topic to each job\n",
    "    job_df['dominant_topic'] = [sorted(lda_model[doc], key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[0][0] if lda_model[doc] else -1 for doc in corpus]\n",
    "    print("\nJob distribution per dominant topic:")\n",
    "    print(job_df['dominant_topic'].value_counts().sort_index())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. Conclusion\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook successfully performed K-Means clustering on job descriptions, determined optimal 'k' using the Elbow Method and Silhouette Score, and visualized the clusters with PCA. Additionally, LDA Topic Modeling was applied to extract skill themes, providing a deeper understanding of job families. The trained K-Means model is saved for use in the Streamlit application."
   ]
  }
 ],
